result.execSummary:
The defendant David M. Huebl was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant David M. Huebl in court with attorney Tara Maureen Guelzow.  Ralph Malcom Uttke appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called @ 9:03 a.m. Agreement stated - Def will plead to charge, withheld sentence, 1 yr probation, counseling, costs, restitution $15.58. State has complied with VWNR. Atty Guelzow and Def agree. Plea quest. reviewed. No contest plea. Constitutional rights, elements and penalties reviewed. Atty Guelzow satisfied. Court finds Def understands, and plea freely & voluntarily made. Factual basis. Court accepts plea and finds guilty of misd. retail theft. Sentencing remarks by Counsel. Statement by Defendant. Court questions Def, gives sentencing remarks. Court will follow agreement - 1 yr probation, withheld jail sentence, counseling as deemed appropriate, may serve in Shawano Co., court costs, DNA sample and surcharge, no credit if revoked, restitution $15.58.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered, without further order of the court, against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. Postconviction rights.
